definition.value: A personal attribute as belonging to a group within a stratified system of categorisation based on a status conferred at birth based on descent, in which individuals have limited or no mobility due to custom or law.
presented in aggregated form as proportion/percentage belonging to a specific caste
A personal attribute that is the state of an individual's mental or physical condition.
A health status attribute that is having been prescribed the use of one or more drugs to improve, maintain or protect one's health.
This entity reflects having been prescribed a medication.  Actual use of the medicine would be captured as a behaviour
A person who is exposed to an intervention.
A human population who are exposed to an intervention.
A person who has not yet reached maturity.
The age until which a person is considered a child will vary in different cultures and for different contexts.  For use in research contexts, the maximum age of a "child" needs to be specified.
A self-identity as belonging to a social group or groups whose members have a common cultural or ancestral heritage.
presented in aggregated form as proportion/percentage who identify as belonging to a specific ethnic group
A self-identity as having a particular gender, which may or may not correspond with sex assigned at birth.

label.value: proportion ability to comprehend spoken intervention language population statistic

definition.value: The proportion of ability to comprehend spoken intervention language in a population.

label.value: ability to read in intervention language population statistic

definition.value: The aggregate of ability to read in intervention language in a population.
A gender identity as having a gender that is not well-described by the binary categories of male or female.
A self-identity as not having a particular gender.
A gender identity that differs from the person's assigned sex at birth.
A gender identity that matches the person's assigned sex at birth.
A bodily quality based on reproductive function or organs.
A biological sex associated with the ability to produce female gametes.
A biological sex associated with the ability to produce male gametes.
An interpersonal role that is realised through a process of promoting and supporting the physical, emotional, social, and intellectual development of a child from infancy to adulthood.
A person can hold a parental role in a child's life without being that child's biological or legal parent.

label.value: percentage ability to read in intervention language population statistic

definition.value: The percentage of ability to read in intervention language in a population.
A family member who is a key caretaker or immediate progenitor of a child.
A parent who provided one of the gametes that resulted in one's conception.
A biological parent who provided an egg.
A biological parent who provided the sperm.
A parent in a parent-child relationship established by a legal adoption process.
An adoptive parent who is female gender.
An adoptive parent who is male gender.
A parent in a parent-child relationship established by the parent's subsequent marriage to one of the child's original biological or legal parents.
A step-parent who is female gender.
A step-parent who is male gender.
A parent who cares for a child who has been placed with them in a foster care arrangement.
A foster parent who is female gender.
A foster parent who is male gender.
A family member who is a person's first generation offspring.
A child relation who is genetically related to their parent.
A biological child who is female gender.
A biological child who is male gender.
A child relation in a parent-child relationship established by a legal adoption process.
An adoptive child who is female gender.
An adoptive child who is male gender.
A child relation in a parent-child relationship established by the parent's subsequent marriage to one of the child's original biological or legal parents.
A stepchild who is female gender.
A stepchild who is male gender.
A child relation in a parent-child relationship created by a foster care arrangement.
A foster child who is female gender.
A foster child who is male gender.
A family member with whom the subject shares a parent.
A sibling with whom the subject shares a biological parent.
A biological sibling who is female gender.
A biological sibling who is male gender.
A sibling with whom the subject shares a parent through a parent-child relationship established by a legal adoption process.
